# URL-Driven Navigation

All user-visible navigation state **must** be reflected in the URL so that any view can be shared as a direct link.

## Rules

- When a component shows a detail/sub-view (e.g. selecting a playlist, opening a collection), use **route params** (`/music/playlists/:id`) or **query params** (`?tab=summary`) instead of local `useState`.
- Use `useParams` and `useNavigate` from `react-router-dom` to read and update the URL.
- Register parameterized routes in `App.tsx` (e.g. `<Route path="/music/playlists/:playlistId" ... />`).
- "Back" buttons should `navigate()` to the parent route, not just clear local state.

## Pattern

```tsx
// ❌ BAD — state-driven, not shareable
const [selected, setSelected] = useState(null);
const open = (id) => { fetchDetail(id).then(setSelected); };
<Button onClick={() => setSelected(null)}>Back</Button>

// ✅ GOOD — URL-driven, shareable
const { itemId } = useParams();
const navigate = useNavigate();
useEffect(() => { if (itemId) fetchDetail(itemId); }, [itemId]);
<Button onClick={() => navigate('/parent')}>Back</Button>
```

## Applies to

- Detail views (playlist, collection, article, album, recipe, etc.)
- Tab selection (use `?tab=` query param)
- Filters that meaningfully change the view
